1
00:00:08,575 --> 00:00:09,975
That's why I decided

2
00:00:09,976 --> 00:00:12,912
I wanted to become
a police officer that day.

3
00:00:14,114 --> 00:00:16,081
- I'm sorry.
- Um...

4
00:00:16,082 --> 00:00:17,916
I should excuse myself now.

5
00:00:17,917 --> 00:00:19,586
Arikeeno.

6
00:00:28,595 --> 00:00:29,662
What's going on?

7
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:31,498
You're looking sad.

8
00:00:32,465 --> 00:00:33,298
Huh?

9
00:00:33,299 --> 00:00:35,100
It's nothing. I'm okay.

10
00:00:35,101 --> 00:00:37,270
I was just being indecisive
because they all look good.

11
00:00:40,073 --> 00:00:42,275
Maybe these. I'll take these two.

12
00:00:44,110 --> 00:00:45,811
You're sharing with your boyfriend?

13
00:00:45,812 --> 00:00:46,813
Excuse me?

14
00:00:47,647 --> 00:00:49,415
Things are not going well with him?

15
00:00:49,416 --> 00:00:50,316
Huh?

16
00:00:51,418 --> 00:00:53,553
<i>Min yi shi wei tian.</i>

17
00:00:54,854 --> 00:00:57,290
What was that? <i>Min yi...</i> what?

18
00:00:57,824 --> 00:01:00,459
<i>Min yi shi wei tian.</i>

19
00:01:00,460 --> 00:01:04,496
It means that the most important activity
for a human being is eating.

20
00:01:04,497 --> 00:01:06,698
It's a Chinese proverb.

21
00:01:06,699 --> 00:01:10,469
If you eat together,
there will be no problem.

22
00:01:10,470 --> 00:01:11,403
But this is for--

23
00:01:11,404 --> 00:01:13,440
Matching stomachs make a good couple.

24
00:01:14,207 --> 00:01:15,141
Cheer up, sweetheart.

25
00:01:19,145 --> 00:01:20,980
Thank you, Auntie.

26
00:01:33,860 --> 00:01:35,328
Satoru...

27
00:01:36,396 --> 00:01:38,698
I don't want to be an obstacle for you.

28
00:01:44,003 --> 00:01:45,371
But I can't hold back anymore.

29
00:01:47,841 --> 00:01:49,576
You are more important to me...

30
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:02,188
<i>Incoming call...</i>

31
00:02:05,458 --> 00:02:08,594
Sir, I'm heading out to do
some legwork on Volunteer.

32
00:02:08,595 --> 00:02:11,263
You're going to Wang Jianbin's factory?

33
00:02:11,264 --> 00:02:13,533
Make sure you coordinate
closely with Koda.

34
00:02:14,534 --> 00:02:16,903
But sir, I can...

35
00:02:17,403 --> 00:02:18,237
go on my own.

36
00:02:18,238 --> 00:02:22,374
You might find this surprising,
but she's sharp-minded

37
00:02:22,375 --> 00:02:24,977
and quite the woman of action.

38
00:02:24,978 --> 00:02:27,747
It's "better roughly right
than precisely wrong," as they say.

39
00:02:28,381 --> 00:02:29,482
Work together in cooperation.

40
00:02:31,417 --> 00:02:32,385
Yes, sir.

41
00:02:33,653 --> 00:02:37,524
Excuse me, Tayama. Could you please
wipe this table clean nicely?

42
00:02:38,024 --> 00:02:38,892
Yes, sir.

43
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:44,229
Don't you think Lieutenant Iiyama
is acting strange today?

44
00:02:44,230 --> 00:02:46,031
I can't blame him.

45
00:02:46,032 --> 00:02:48,534
An extra burden is going to be put on him.

46
00:02:48,535 --> 00:02:50,502
You mean, the person who's coming today?

47
00:02:50,503 --> 00:02:51,504
Yeah.

48
00:02:56,743 --> 00:02:58,344
What is he like?

49
00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:06,486
If I were to describe him in one word,
it will be an "ogre".

50
00:03:07,153 --> 00:03:08,655
Did you say an ogre?

51
00:03:09,889 --> 00:03:11,190
You mean, a monster?

52
00:03:11,191 --> 00:03:13,492
For us, he could be like a devil.

53
00:03:13,493 --> 00:03:14,694
Devil?

54
00:03:15,428 --> 00:03:18,597
Or he may be a dragon
that could carry us to heaven.

55
00:03:18,598 --> 00:03:19,799
Dragon?

56
00:03:21,868 --> 00:03:24,503
You're not making sense at all.

57
00:03:24,504 --> 00:03:26,339
Whatever he is,

58
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:29,642
our division will have a handful for sure.

59
00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:39,518
Hi, Mr. Shack.

60
00:03:39,519 --> 00:03:41,520
- You're late.
- I'm sorry.

61
00:03:41,521 --> 00:03:44,122
Were you already worried about lunch?

62
00:03:44,123 --> 00:03:45,625
Well, you know...

63
00:03:46,526 --> 00:03:48,728
Why are you coming with me
instead of Mr. Arikino?

64
00:03:50,330 --> 00:03:51,430
I'm so sorry.

65
00:03:51,431 --> 00:03:53,766
Just don't stand in my way.

66
00:03:55,068 --> 00:03:58,271
Lieutenant Iiyama
is totally overestimating you.

67
00:03:59,038 --> 00:04:00,006
Oh, here she is.

68
00:04:01,441 --> 00:04:02,642
Hello, Mengqi.

69
00:04:05,645 --> 00:04:07,580
It's great to see you.

70
00:04:08,181 --> 00:04:10,416
I brought some food.
How about you join us?

71
00:04:10,817 --> 00:04:13,286
You're here again? Stop it!

72
00:04:14,053 --> 00:04:17,356
Last time, you didn't take
the Guangdong food I brought,

73
00:04:17,357 --> 00:04:19,392
so today, I brought Sichuan <i>mapo tofu</i>
with rice.

74
00:04:19,959 --> 00:04:20,793
Last time?

75
00:04:21,394 --> 00:04:23,596
You come many times, but I don't say.

76
00:04:24,097 --> 00:04:26,798
I don't want to talk about Volunteer.

77
00:04:26,799 --> 00:04:29,302
Mengqi, wait.

78
00:04:35,608 --> 00:04:38,978
Go ahead and call me
when you feel like you want to talk.

79
00:04:54,627 --> 00:04:56,629
My lunch was in there, too.

80
00:04:59,966 --> 00:05:04,203
<i>So far, she's the only clue we have
to how Volunteer operates.</i>

81
00:05:05,738 --> 00:05:09,041
Can you somehow talk to Lin Mengqi?

82
00:05:09,042 --> 00:05:11,710
If she could call me at least,

83
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:13,979
I think I could somehow manage
to pull it off.

84
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:15,080
I wish she would...

85
00:05:15,081 --> 00:05:16,482
Oops. I'm sorry.

86
00:05:19,285 --> 00:05:22,288
You look pretty good with that green hair.

87
00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:26,224
I'm sorry, but I can't speak Chinese.

88
00:05:26,225 --> 00:05:28,960
Forget it. Um...

89
00:05:28,961 --> 00:05:30,696
Where’s the International
Investigation Division?

90
00:05:30,697 --> 00:05:33,533
- Uh...
- I think he's looking for something.

91
00:05:37,103 --> 00:05:39,104
INCOMING CALL
MARI KODA

92
00:05:39,105 --> 00:05:41,341
Tell him I'm getting an interpreter.

93
00:05:46,012 --> 00:05:48,281
I'm sorry. My bad.
I don't need an interpreter.

94
00:05:55,922 --> 00:05:58,157
Lieutenant Agawa?

95
00:05:59,525 --> 00:06:00,626
Lieutenant?

96
00:06:01,594 --> 00:06:06,499
I'm your partner starting from today,
Greenhead.

97
00:06:08,034 --> 00:06:08,901
You're my partner?

98
00:06:16,943 --> 00:06:19,679
Is everyone here? Then, please go ahead.

99
00:06:20,980 --> 00:06:22,581
I'm Hiroya Agawa.

100
00:06:22,582 --> 00:06:23,548
‎INTERNATIONAL INVESTIGATION DIVISION

101
00:06:23,549 --> 00:06:26,485
As of today, I've been assigned
to Higashi Shinjuku Police Station.

102
00:06:26,486 --> 00:06:28,520
I'm joining the International
Investigation Division

103
00:06:28,521 --> 00:06:30,789
of the Organized Crime Section.

104
00:06:30,790 --> 00:06:31,890
All right.

105
00:06:31,891 --> 00:06:34,025
Lieutenant Agawa was transferred

106
00:06:34,026 --> 00:06:36,528
from the Shinbashi West's
Community Affairs Division.

107
00:06:36,529 --> 00:06:37,462
But prior to that,

108
00:06:37,463 --> 00:06:40,866
he was with the International Division
at Kamiazabu Police Station.

109
00:06:40,867 --> 00:06:44,102
He's fluent in Chinese
and has a lot of experience.

110
00:06:44,103 --> 00:06:47,240
He's what you call
"a veteran of many battles."

111
00:06:47,940 --> 00:06:52,344
Koda, make sure to learn
as much as you can from him

112
00:06:52,345 --> 00:06:53,980
while you're working together as partners.

113
00:06:54,914 --> 00:06:57,483
I would be more at ease on my own.

114
00:06:58,785 --> 00:07:03,054
Mitsui's team continues to track down
the safehouse of the suspects

115
00:07:03,055 --> 00:07:05,791
responsible for the recent
shop robberies in the area.

116
00:07:05,792 --> 00:07:07,859
And Shiraishi, your team will...

117
00:07:07,860 --> 00:07:10,096
Come on, let's go.

118
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:12,031
Yes?

119
00:07:15,334 --> 00:07:16,168
‎SHINJUKU SERIAL CONVENIENCE STORE
‎ROBBERY CASE

120
00:07:16,169 --> 00:07:18,171
- Next, we will...
- Something important is...

121
00:07:21,340 --> 00:07:22,909
- Hey, wait.
- Wait.

122
00:07:25,411 --> 00:07:26,645
Those two have left.

123
00:07:26,646 --> 00:07:27,847
What?

124
00:07:28,414 --> 00:07:31,584
Lieutenant, our briefing is not over yet.

125
00:07:32,351 --> 00:07:34,653
The Detective Division
is leading the case, right?

126
00:07:34,654 --> 00:07:36,856
Our division is just there
to fill up the room.

127
00:07:37,490 --> 00:07:39,090
We get things done faster

128
00:07:39,091 --> 00:07:41,727
by gathering intel on the field
instead of sitting in meetings.

129
00:07:46,933 --> 00:07:48,768
Boss, when are we going?

130
00:07:53,506 --> 00:07:56,843
- Mr. Agawa, everything alright?
- Mr. Agawa, it's great to see you.

131
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:02,748
These two scumbags have been robbing
convenience stores.

132
00:08:04,283 --> 00:08:06,018
Do you know them?

133
00:08:07,019 --> 00:08:07,887
No, I don't.

134
00:08:09,388 --> 00:08:11,958
These are familiar faces, aren't they?

135
00:08:16,829 --> 00:08:20,298
I'm surprised they talked.

136
00:08:20,299 --> 00:08:22,368
They're from Shanghai.

137
00:08:22,969 --> 00:08:25,538
The suspects are
from Northeast China, right?

138
00:08:26,205 --> 00:08:29,108
So, they don't get along very well.

139
00:08:30,676 --> 00:08:33,678
You can't lump them all together
into one category.

140
00:08:33,679 --> 00:08:36,047
Each province has its own language,

141
00:08:36,048 --> 00:08:38,651
and people grow up
in entirely different environments.

142
00:08:39,385 --> 00:08:40,386
That's interesting.

143
00:08:41,187 --> 00:08:43,889
Should we go check out
their potential safehouse?

144
00:08:43,890 --> 00:08:45,091
No, thanks.

145
00:08:45,591 --> 00:08:48,760
Greenhead, relay the information
to the incident room.

146
00:08:48,761 --> 00:08:49,662
Pardon me?

147
00:08:50,162 --> 00:08:52,632
We need to let
the Detective Division shine.

148
00:08:55,301 --> 00:08:56,135
Yes, sir.

149
00:08:57,737 --> 00:09:00,106
<i>Miss Koda finally has a partner?</i>

150
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:04,677
I thought no one except Mr. Arikino
could handle her.

151
00:09:05,177 --> 00:09:06,745
When you think about it,

152
00:09:06,746 --> 00:09:09,948
I wonder why Miss Koda
favors Mr. Arikino so much.

153
00:09:09,949 --> 00:09:11,716
They often eat together, don't they?

154
00:09:11,717 --> 00:09:14,353
They get along
because they have "matching stomachs."

155
00:09:16,155 --> 00:09:17,189
That's it.

156
00:09:22,228 --> 00:09:25,865
TOKYO METROPOLITAN POLICE DEPARTMENT

157
00:09:34,006 --> 00:09:34,840
Hey, Arikeeno.

158
00:09:37,510 --> 00:09:39,612
I thought you might be somewhere
around here.

159
00:09:40,613 --> 00:09:41,447
Are you doing all right?

160
00:09:42,315 --> 00:09:43,149
Yes, I am.

161
00:09:45,351 --> 00:09:46,685
I'm sorry about the other day.

162
00:09:46,686 --> 00:09:47,853
No problem.

163
00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:51,424
You'll have this, right?

164
00:09:53,859 --> 00:09:55,193
Well, I've already eaten.

165
00:09:55,194 --> 00:09:58,664
Are you kidding me?
I bought two on purpose.

166
00:10:02,668 --> 00:10:03,970
Here we go.

167
00:10:12,044 --> 00:10:15,414
- There's someone new at our division and...
- Um...

168
00:10:16,515 --> 00:10:18,651
I'm sorry, but I have to go.

169
00:10:21,287 --> 00:10:23,289
What's the matter? Is something wrong?

170
00:10:24,290 --> 00:10:26,591
If you want to talk, I'll listen.

171
00:10:26,592 --> 00:10:28,327
No. Nothing's wrong.

172
00:10:29,228 --> 00:10:30,395
But...

173
00:10:30,396 --> 00:10:31,297
Excuse me.

174
00:10:32,632 --> 00:10:33,499
Wait, Arikeeno.

175
00:10:42,074 --> 00:10:45,044
I had no idea that Mari was there
at that scene.

176
00:10:48,748 --> 00:10:50,783
Have you talked to her since then?

177
00:10:51,717 --> 00:10:52,685
No.

178
00:10:53,886 --> 00:10:56,389
She doesn't know anything about me.

179
00:10:57,723 --> 00:11:00,092
That's because you don't tell her
anything, right?

180
00:11:04,230 --> 00:11:06,298
You know something
that's always bothered me?

181
00:11:06,799 --> 00:11:09,167
You always hold back like that.

182
00:11:09,168 --> 00:11:11,704
That's such a bad habit of yours,
Arikeeno.

183
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:14,540
Leave me alone.

184
00:11:20,946 --> 00:11:24,050
I think she is well aware
that you are holding back.

185
00:11:25,985 --> 00:11:29,088
But she still keeps the same stance
with you.

186
00:11:30,890 --> 00:11:33,192
People like that are hard to find,
you know?

187
00:11:42,568 --> 00:11:44,937
There you are. You found this place okay?

188
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:46,806
Yes.

189
00:11:47,573 --> 00:11:48,441
Have a seat.

190
00:11:50,676 --> 00:11:51,911
What would you like to drink?

191
00:11:55,347 --> 00:11:58,517
I'm going to go do some shopping.
Eat these for now.

192
00:11:59,285 --> 00:12:00,152
See ya.

193
00:12:00,686 --> 00:12:02,054
- See you.
- Bye.

194
00:12:12,264 --> 00:12:13,365
I heard

195
00:12:14,333 --> 00:12:17,169
that you now have
a Chinese speaking investigator.

196
00:12:18,537 --> 00:12:19,371
Yes,

197
00:12:20,306 --> 00:12:22,675
we actually do.

198
00:12:25,578 --> 00:12:28,614
Since I don't get those random
work requests from you anymore,

199
00:12:30,416 --> 00:12:31,684
it's made my life easier.

200
00:12:34,854 --> 00:12:36,622
I knew you'd say that.

201
00:12:38,624 --> 00:12:40,291
Oh, I know! Listen now.

202
00:12:40,292 --> 00:12:42,427
Do you remember Lin Mengqi?

203
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:43,762
She's the one who introduced Volunteer

204
00:12:43,763 --> 00:12:46,499
to Wang Jianbin,
the man who protected the baby.

205
00:12:47,133 --> 00:12:51,837
I went to see her so many times
to ask some questions,

206
00:12:52,805 --> 00:12:55,040
but she just wouldn't talk to me.

207
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:59,278
I bet you've been trying to build
a rapport with her using food again.

208
00:13:00,579 --> 00:13:02,213
How did you know that?

209
00:13:02,214 --> 00:13:05,417
Were you watching me go around
carrying food?

210
00:13:06,285 --> 00:13:08,287
I don't need to see it to know.

211
00:13:10,422 --> 00:13:13,091
I just wish the folks at headquarters

212
00:13:13,092 --> 00:13:15,160
were more serious
about investigating Volunteer.

213
00:13:15,161 --> 00:13:18,397
Then I wouldn't have to be out here.

214
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:23,234
Anyhow,

215
00:13:23,235 --> 00:13:27,172
Mengqi seems to be avoiding the police
and wouldn't talk.

216
00:13:27,173 --> 00:13:31,477
And I'm not sure how much Japanese
she can speak.

217
00:13:31,977 --> 00:13:33,145
So, I was wondering

218
00:13:34,180 --> 00:13:36,014
if you could come on Monday and--

219
00:13:36,015 --> 00:13:38,350
Actually, on that day,

220
00:13:39,151 --> 00:13:40,853
I have something else going on.

221
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:43,489
I didn't even finish my sentence.

222
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:51,563
All right, then.
If you are not going to help me,

223
00:13:51,564 --> 00:13:53,165
I'll ask Lieutenant Agawa.

224
00:13:55,201 --> 00:13:56,068
Agawa?

225
00:13:59,104 --> 00:14:00,172
You mean,

226
00:14:01,373 --> 00:14:02,441
Hiroya Agawa?

227
00:14:04,276 --> 00:14:06,211
Um, yes.

228
00:14:06,212 --> 00:14:10,982
He got transferred last week
and we are partners now.

229
00:14:10,983 --> 00:14:13,118
Do you know anything
about Lieutenant Agawa?

230
00:14:16,488 --> 00:14:18,324
You should never trust him.

231
00:14:23,262 --> 00:14:28,667
YAKITORI, LOCAL SAKE, DRAFT BEER, SOURS

232
00:14:39,278 --> 00:14:43,982
<i>Hey there, Lieutenant.
I heard you're back in the field.</i>

233
00:14:43,983 --> 00:14:45,784
<i>Congratulations.</i>

234
00:14:49,021 --> 00:14:50,256
Is it Volunteer?

235
00:14:51,991 --> 00:14:55,461
Your promotion makes me happy too.

236
00:14:56,962 --> 00:15:00,566
You know that people in higher positions
tend to keep their secrets well.

237
00:15:02,668 --> 00:15:04,970
Where are you now?

238
00:15:06,171 --> 00:15:08,007
<i>Not far from you at all.</i>

239
00:15:08,741 --> 00:15:11,410
<i>The police has changed a lot
and has become rigid.</i>

240
00:15:12,011 --> 00:15:13,379
<i>So, I'm moving around.</i>

241
00:15:16,048 --> 00:15:17,983
Let's make money together again.

242
00:15:19,652 --> 00:15:21,186
You'll hear from me soon.

243
00:15:37,002 --> 00:15:39,438
TOKYO METROPOLITAN POLICE DEPARTMENT

244
00:15:41,707 --> 00:15:42,541
What are you doing?

245
00:15:45,811 --> 00:15:48,614
Hello, Arikino. It's been a while.

246
00:15:50,482 --> 00:15:51,817
It's all right.

247
00:15:52,618 --> 00:15:53,886
Will you excuse us for a minute?

248
00:15:54,386 --> 00:15:55,287
Yes, sir.

249
00:16:01,660 --> 00:16:03,395
Why didn't you let me know

250
00:16:04,263 --> 00:16:06,298
that Agawa would be back in the field?

251
00:16:06,999 --> 00:16:08,566
You didn't even properly greet me.

252
00:16:08,567 --> 00:16:10,034
YUKIHIRO TOYOZUMI
SUPERINTENDENT

253
00:16:10,035 --> 00:16:13,004
Why would you send Agawa
back into the field?

254
00:16:13,005 --> 00:16:15,574
It's just a routine transfer this time.

255
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:17,409
You're lying.

256
00:16:19,211 --> 00:16:23,115
I personally haven't taken my eyes
off Hiroya Agawa yet.

257
00:16:24,149 --> 00:16:26,752
I will investigate
and expose him this time.

258
00:16:28,087 --> 00:16:30,922
Four years ago,
headquarters dismissed my report,

259
00:16:30,923 --> 00:16:33,993
saying that it lacked objective evidence.

260
00:16:35,494 --> 00:16:37,629
If you couldn't bring charges to him then,

261
00:16:38,230 --> 00:16:39,231
why would you try now?

262
00:16:40,099 --> 00:16:42,334
You know the Volunteer case in Shinjuku?

263
00:16:42,868 --> 00:16:46,205
It feels just like the case
Agawa was involved in four years ago.

264
00:16:47,639 --> 00:16:51,076
If Volunteer makes a move,
Agawa might make a move too.

265
00:16:52,644 --> 00:16:54,113
How would you investigate?

266
00:16:56,415 --> 00:16:59,218
<i>Are you going to have his partner
spy on him again</i>

267
00:17:00,652 --> 00:17:01,954
<i>like you did with Oda?</i>

268
00:17:03,956 --> 00:17:05,724
<i>If you involve Sergeant Koda,</i>

269
00:17:07,459 --> 00:17:09,194
I won't forgive you this time.

270
00:17:18,303 --> 00:17:22,241
Shin-Okubo is a town
with many gods, isn't it?

271
00:17:23,809 --> 00:17:24,877
With many gods?

272
00:17:25,644 --> 00:17:28,747
There's such a variety of food
from different countries here.

273
00:17:30,315 --> 00:17:32,151
<i>There are Christian churches.</i>

274
00:17:32,951 --> 00:17:34,953
<i>There's a Hindu temple,</i>

275
00:17:35,521 --> 00:17:37,855
<i>and even a Taiwanese Taoist temple.</i>

276
00:17:37,856 --> 00:17:40,625
<i>Of course, Japanese Shinto shrines
are there, too.</i>

277
00:17:40,626 --> 00:17:42,960
I guess it means
you need spiritual support

278
00:17:42,961 --> 00:17:45,531
when you live far away
from your home country.

279
00:17:47,032 --> 00:17:48,566
<i>Wherever people have their gods,</i>

280
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:51,537
<i>that's also where their community gathers.</i>

281
00:17:52,938 --> 00:17:54,239
But anyway,

282
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:57,976
people who can believe in something
wholeheartedly are strong.

283
00:18:01,547 --> 00:18:03,615
You should never trust him.

284
00:18:08,754 --> 00:18:09,922
Lieutenant,

285
00:18:11,790 --> 00:18:13,192
do you know Volunteer?

286
00:18:15,727 --> 00:18:16,829
Volunteer?

287
00:18:18,330 --> 00:18:21,933
I was wondering if you came across
that name when you worked

288
00:18:21,934 --> 00:18:23,635
at Kamiazabu Police Station.

289
00:18:24,169 --> 00:18:26,038
I may have.

290
00:18:26,805 --> 00:18:28,806
Is that the guy who's called Volunteer

291
00:18:28,807 --> 00:18:31,509
because he makes free passports
for illegal residents?

292
00:18:31,510 --> 00:18:34,279
Yes. That's it.
Do you know anything about him?

293
00:18:37,282 --> 00:18:39,317
That's an urban legend.

294
00:18:39,318 --> 00:18:43,122
I've heard about him somewhere,
but it never went beyond rumors.

295
00:18:45,424 --> 00:18:48,560
Or do you have a reliable source
of information now?

296
00:18:52,431 --> 00:18:54,733
So far, what I know for certain is...

297
00:18:57,269 --> 00:18:59,505
Zero! There's nothing.

298
00:19:00,405 --> 00:19:02,573
But I have my own theory.

299
00:19:02,574 --> 00:19:08,313
Given the scale of their operation,
I believe it's an organized operation.

300
00:19:16,288 --> 00:19:18,090
They make passports for free

301
00:19:19,825 --> 00:19:22,094
and they ask for favors in return.

302
00:19:23,529 --> 00:19:25,430
That's their approach.

303
00:19:25,964 --> 00:19:28,500
For example,
that's how they recruit mules.

304
00:19:30,469 --> 00:19:31,537
In Wang Jianbin's case,

305
00:19:32,337 --> 00:19:36,275
<i>he was asked to take a kidnapped child
out of the country.</i>

306
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:41,779
That's how they send people who are
illegally overstaying to the mainland

307
00:19:41,780 --> 00:19:45,584
and sell them to human traffickers
in exchange for a reward.

308
00:19:46,919 --> 00:19:48,554
If they can be used as mules as well,

309
00:19:49,421 --> 00:19:50,589
it's killing two birds with one stone.

310
00:19:52,791 --> 00:19:57,462
I haven't found out
when Volunteer started operating in Japan.

311
00:19:58,664 --> 00:20:03,235
But there's a high chance
that there are already many victims.

312
00:20:04,136 --> 00:20:05,937
We need to expose

313
00:20:05,938 --> 00:20:08,473
the full extent of the organization
as soon as possible.

314
00:20:10,542 --> 00:20:14,246
Well, even if your hypothesis
is correct, I doubt

315
00:20:14,746 --> 00:20:16,548
headquarters would take any action.

316
00:20:17,549 --> 00:20:18,784
Why wouldn't they?

317
00:20:19,618 --> 00:20:21,286
The victims are invisible to us.

318
00:20:22,621 --> 00:20:26,892
Illegal residents are not even allowed
to live in Japan in the first place.

319
00:20:27,859 --> 00:20:30,761
The ones that are targeted
are not Japanese,

320
00:20:30,762 --> 00:20:33,031
and the victims are not killed in Japan.

321
00:20:34,933 --> 00:20:37,368
Whatever happens
to those illegal residents

322
00:20:37,369 --> 00:20:39,771
has nothing to do
with ordinary Japanese citizens.

323
00:20:50,182 --> 00:20:51,083
Oh.

324
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:53,218
Excuse me.

325
00:20:57,489 --> 00:20:58,490
Hello?

326
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:01,393
<i>I can't...</i>

327
00:21:04,730 --> 00:21:06,665
<i>I can't talk about Volunteer.</i>

328
00:21:07,766 --> 00:21:08,767
<i>It's difficult.</i>

329
00:21:10,002 --> 00:21:10,902
Mengqi, is that you?

330
00:21:11,803 --> 00:21:12,638
Mengqi?

331
00:21:14,539 --> 00:21:17,575
Please bring Officer Oda
from Kamiazabu Police Station.

332
00:21:17,576 --> 00:21:19,378
I will talk to Officer Oda.

333
00:21:20,679 --> 00:21:23,415
<i>Officer Oda? Do you know his first name?</i>

334
00:21:24,883 --> 00:21:26,284
Other people, no.

335
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:28,520
Only to you and Officer Oda.

336
00:21:29,388 --> 00:21:30,455
<i>Okay.</i>

337
00:21:31,189 --> 00:21:32,023
<i>Meng--</i>

338
00:21:32,024 --> 00:21:32,958
Mengqi?

339
00:21:37,663 --> 00:21:38,930
Oda?

340
00:21:39,865 --> 00:21:41,900
Satoru Oda from Kamiazabu Police Station?

341
00:21:45,237 --> 00:21:46,438
Do you know him?

342
00:21:47,406 --> 00:21:50,676
Officer Satoru Oda was my former partner.

343
00:21:57,516 --> 00:21:59,017
He was?

344
00:22:00,819 --> 00:22:01,687
And...

345
00:22:02,821 --> 00:22:03,655
So...

346
00:22:04,356 --> 00:22:07,092
which station is he at now?

347
00:22:09,928 --> 00:22:10,762
<i>Oda is...</i>

348
00:22:13,465 --> 00:22:14,399
<i>He's dead.</i>

349
00:22:19,471 --> 00:22:20,572
He died four years ago.

350
00:22:38,390 --> 00:22:41,993
YOYOGI PHANTOM KILLER INCIDENT

351
00:22:43,862 --> 00:22:45,797
"Yoyogi Phantom Killer Incident"?

352
00:22:55,674 --> 00:22:58,909
YOYOGI PHANTOM KILLER INCIDENT
THE PERPETRATOR WAS CAUGHT IN THE ACT

353
00:22:58,910 --> 00:23:02,180
"...were awarded the Police Chief Award."

354
00:23:07,819 --> 00:23:09,154
Oh, that's Arikeeno.

355
00:23:12,290 --> 00:23:13,525
And Lieutenant Yanagi?

356
00:23:20,532 --> 00:23:21,833
He's the one from...

357
00:23:34,546 --> 00:23:35,714
Lieutenant Yanagi.

358
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:40,051
What do you need this early?

359
00:23:40,952 --> 00:23:42,053
I'm sorry,

360
00:23:42,587 --> 00:23:46,425
but there's something I need to ask you.

361
00:23:48,760 --> 00:23:49,728
What is it?

362
00:23:52,931 --> 00:23:57,102
How did Sergeant Satoru Oda die?

363
00:24:01,206 --> 00:24:03,275
I know it's insensitive of me to ask.

364
00:24:03,875 --> 00:24:06,410
You were his supervisor

365
00:24:06,411 --> 00:24:08,880
when he was a new recruit
at the station, right?

366
00:24:09,648 --> 00:24:11,016
Why do you bring this up now?

367
00:24:15,153 --> 00:24:16,455
Eight years ago,

368
00:24:17,055 --> 00:24:19,657
you arrested the Yoyogi Phantom Killer.

369
00:24:19,658 --> 00:24:20,591
YOYOGI PHANTOM KILLER INCIDENT

370
00:24:20,592 --> 00:24:22,461
And you received
the Police Chief Award together.

371
00:24:26,264 --> 00:24:27,265
Actually,

372
00:24:29,801 --> 00:24:31,303
I was at the scene when it happened.

373
00:24:35,874 --> 00:24:38,210
And Sergeant Oda helped me.

374
00:24:44,483 --> 00:24:46,751
I don't know
how you even found the courage.

375
00:24:47,352 --> 00:24:49,287
Not everyone can face a criminal.

376
00:25:06,538 --> 00:25:08,273
Why are you giving me such a dirty look

377
00:25:09,107 --> 00:25:10,642
when this could be a nice reunion?

378
00:25:13,812 --> 00:25:15,046
<i>I bet you've heard about it.</i>

379
00:25:16,314 --> 00:25:18,049
A detective from Kamiazabu Police Station

380
00:25:18,884 --> 00:25:22,587
had been misinterpreting a lot
during questioning and interviews.

381
00:25:23,855 --> 00:25:25,924
And that Arikino leaked the information.

382
00:25:28,894 --> 00:25:29,727
Yes, I have.

383
00:25:29,728 --> 00:25:31,729
EXCLUSIVE SCOOP:
THE DARKNESS INSIDE THE POLICE FORCE!

384
00:25:31,730 --> 00:25:34,231
"DELIBERATE MISINTERPRETATION"

385
00:25:34,232 --> 00:25:35,366
AN INSIDER OF KAMIAZABU POLICE STATION

386
00:25:35,367 --> 00:25:37,636
<i>An attorney for a Chinese suspect</i>

387
00:25:39,204 --> 00:25:41,740
had concerns
about the police's interpretation.

388
00:25:42,374 --> 00:25:44,809
He requested the audio recording
of the questioning sessions

389
00:25:45,310 --> 00:25:46,745
during the trial.

390
00:25:49,180 --> 00:25:50,482
Kamiazabu Police Station stated

391
00:25:51,283 --> 00:25:53,485
that the sessions were not recorded.

392
00:25:54,719 --> 00:25:58,490
But in reality,
the audio recordings did exist.

393
00:26:02,327 --> 00:26:06,164
Part of the recordings
was leaked to a weekly magazine,

394
00:26:07,265 --> 00:26:08,533
exposing the misinterpretation.

395
00:26:12,604 --> 00:26:14,673
Two detectives were mentioned
in the article

396
00:26:15,240 --> 00:26:17,642
and were condemned by the media.

397
00:26:19,110 --> 00:26:20,378
One of them was the detective

398
00:26:22,514 --> 00:26:24,883
<i>who interpreted during the questioning.</i>

399
00:26:25,817 --> 00:26:27,085
<i>It was Lieutenant Agawa.</i>

400
00:26:28,453 --> 00:26:29,421
What?

401
00:26:30,288 --> 00:26:31,489
It was Lieutenant Agawa?

402
00:26:31,990 --> 00:26:32,857
And the other one was...

403
00:26:36,394 --> 00:26:37,796
<i>his partner at that time.</i>

404
00:26:38,597 --> 00:26:39,864
<i>It was Satoru Oda.</i>

405
00:26:44,135 --> 00:26:45,804
One week after the article was published,

406
00:26:48,073 --> 00:26:48,907
Oda did...

407
00:26:51,343 --> 00:26:52,611
He committed suicide.

408
00:27:02,787 --> 00:27:03,855
So now you know.

409
00:27:05,223 --> 00:27:09,227
You now understand why Arikino
always keeps people at a distance.

410
00:27:12,197 --> 00:27:13,198
He was despised

411
00:27:14,699 --> 00:27:17,035
and hated by everyone at the station.

412
00:27:21,573 --> 00:27:22,674
But still,

413
00:27:23,274 --> 00:27:27,679
why did people think that Arikeeno
was the one who leaked the information?

414
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:32,182
How was he related
to this misinterpretation incident?

415
00:27:32,183 --> 00:27:33,117
At that time,

416
00:27:33,118 --> 00:27:36,287
Arikino was with the Security Division
at Kamiazabu Police Station.

417
00:27:38,023 --> 00:27:40,859
He had been requested
by Superintendent Toyozumi

418
00:27:41,960 --> 00:27:44,596
to conduct an internal investigation
into Agawa.

419
00:27:46,231 --> 00:27:49,067
So the only suspicious person

420
00:27:49,567 --> 00:27:53,638
who was familiar
with the inside information was him.

421
00:28:01,246 --> 00:28:04,616
That kind of look is typically given
to perpetrators.

422
00:28:11,122 --> 00:28:12,557
Are you repeating the same thing?

423
00:28:56,835 --> 00:28:57,836
Lieutenant Agawa.

424
00:29:00,739 --> 00:29:01,673
Lieutenant Agawa.

425
00:29:04,776 --> 00:29:06,911
Can I talk to you for a moment?

426
00:29:18,089 --> 00:29:19,691
You want to talk about four years ago?

427
00:29:24,062 --> 00:29:24,896
Yes, I do.

428
00:29:26,998 --> 00:29:28,433
Well, how should I say?

429
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:33,271
If you look into Oda's case,
you're inevitably led to that incident.

430
00:29:34,172 --> 00:29:37,407
I should have told you about it earlier.

431
00:29:37,408 --> 00:29:38,576
Forgive me.

432
00:29:39,377 --> 00:29:40,545
Sure.

433
00:29:43,915 --> 00:29:45,850
I don't know if it's appropriate
to say this,

434
00:29:46,618 --> 00:29:49,487
but misinterpretations can happen
no matter how hard you try.

435
00:29:50,321 --> 00:29:53,625
Misunderstandings can happen
even between Japanese speakers.

436
00:29:55,059 --> 00:29:58,329
So, when more than two languages
are involved, it's inevitable.

437
00:30:00,999 --> 00:30:02,467
What's important is how you respond

438
00:30:03,301 --> 00:30:05,603
when you realize you've misinterpreted.

439
00:30:06,905 --> 00:30:08,439
Can we acknowledge our mistake

440
00:30:09,407 --> 00:30:12,043
and offer the correct interpretation?

441
00:30:17,048 --> 00:30:19,450
I'm just repeating
what someone I know always says.

442
00:30:22,987 --> 00:30:24,589
Ouch, that hits a nerve.

443
00:30:26,791 --> 00:30:29,861
I failed to do that back then.

444
00:30:33,531 --> 00:30:37,135
I deserved to be taken off the field
because of that.

445
00:30:39,304 --> 00:30:40,271
But here I am.

446
00:30:42,340 --> 00:30:44,843
I somehow made it back on the field.

447
00:30:46,644 --> 00:30:48,379
Maybe it's God.

448
00:30:49,747 --> 00:30:51,783
Maybe God has given me one last chance.

449
00:30:54,586 --> 00:30:55,854
What do you mean, "last chance"?

450
00:30:56,921 --> 00:30:58,389
When you reach this age,

451
00:30:59,724 --> 00:31:01,626
you start to see, you know...

452
00:31:03,228 --> 00:31:04,062
You see the mountain.

453
00:31:06,331 --> 00:31:07,398
The mountain?

454
00:31:09,734 --> 00:31:13,671
You begin to see the last mountain
you can climb.

455
00:31:27,118 --> 00:31:28,152
What is it?

456
00:31:31,522 --> 00:31:33,291
Oda gave me a look like that, too.

457
00:31:43,134 --> 00:31:44,569
I know you're debating,

458
00:31:45,803 --> 00:31:46,838
Greenhead.

459
00:31:48,306 --> 00:31:51,542
You're not sure if you can trust me
as a partner.

460
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:15,233
ODA

461
00:32:30,982 --> 00:32:34,685
I'm sorry for contacting you
about your brother so suddenly.

462
00:32:34,686 --> 00:32:35,687
It's all right.

463
00:32:37,121 --> 00:32:39,724
These are his personal belongings
that I've kept.

464
00:32:41,693 --> 00:32:43,327
Our mother got rid of everything left

465
00:32:43,328 --> 00:32:46,764
at our parents' house because it was
too hard for her to see it.

466
00:32:49,667 --> 00:32:51,201
Can I touch them?

467
00:32:51,202 --> 00:32:52,103
Go ahead.

468
00:33:05,616 --> 00:33:08,086
How about things like his cell phone
or day planner?

469
00:33:08,953 --> 00:33:12,190
The police took them,
and we still haven't gotten them back.

470
00:33:13,091 --> 00:33:16,626
They said they couldn't find
an SD card or something.

471
00:33:16,627 --> 00:33:19,130
They asked me many times
if it was among his stuff.

472
00:33:19,931 --> 00:33:20,998
An SD card?

473
00:33:20,999 --> 00:33:21,899
Yes.

474
00:33:28,940 --> 00:33:31,376
I see that your brother was a smoker.

475
00:33:32,043 --> 00:33:36,114
He may have been, but he never smoked
in front of his family.

476
00:33:39,851 --> 00:33:42,820
- I'll make some tea.
- Thank you.

477
00:34:10,848 --> 00:34:12,550
- By the way...
- Yes?

478
00:34:13,918 --> 00:34:18,589
Was your brother in a relationship
at that time?

479
00:34:21,192 --> 00:34:25,029
He never discussed
that kind of thing with his family.

480
00:34:28,933 --> 00:34:30,068
I see.

481
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:39,010
<i>Please bring Officer Oda
from Kamiazabu Police Station.</i>

482
00:34:39,777 --> 00:34:41,746
<i>- I will talk to Officer Oda.
- Oda is...</i>

483
00:34:42,914 --> 00:34:43,948
He's dead.

484
00:34:44,515 --> 00:34:45,882
<i>So now you know.</i>

485
00:34:45,883 --> 00:34:49,954
<i>You now understand why Arikino
always keeps people at a distance.</i>

486
00:35:08,306 --> 00:35:10,475
Hello? Lieutenant Yanagi?

487
00:35:11,242 --> 00:35:12,243
What's the matter?

488
00:35:16,481 --> 00:35:17,482
What?

489
00:35:31,596 --> 00:35:32,830
What's the matter?

490
00:35:35,533 --> 00:35:37,835
I know you're busy. I'm so sorry.

491
00:35:38,569 --> 00:35:39,403
It's okay.

492
00:35:42,707 --> 00:35:44,208
It's about Lin Mengqi.

493
00:35:45,343 --> 00:35:46,244
She was murdered.

494
00:35:47,778 --> 00:35:48,779
She was murdered?

495
00:35:51,082 --> 00:35:53,217
<i>With a single slice
to her right neck artery.</i>

496
00:35:54,285 --> 00:35:56,787
<i>They say
it's probably not an amateur's job.</i>

497
00:35:59,290 --> 00:36:00,391
<i>I think she was killed</i>

498
00:36:01,225 --> 00:36:03,527
<i>because I contacted her about Volunteer.</i>

499
00:36:03,528 --> 00:36:04,428
MARI KODA

500
00:36:06,430 --> 00:36:08,065
So, I can't back out.

501
00:36:09,467 --> 00:36:10,568
I can't back out anymore.

502
00:36:14,906 --> 00:36:15,840
You know what she said?

503
00:36:18,376 --> 00:36:20,611
She said she could talk about Volunteer

504
00:36:21,846 --> 00:36:24,315
only to Officer Oda
from Kamiazabu Police Station.

505
00:36:26,884 --> 00:36:27,885
To Oda?

506
00:36:28,886 --> 00:36:29,720
Yes.

507
00:36:31,122 --> 00:36:32,390
Arikeeno,

508
00:36:33,357 --> 00:36:35,459
you were close to Officer Oda, right?

509
00:36:38,829 --> 00:36:40,765
We were at the police academy together.

510
00:36:43,134 --> 00:36:44,669
I looked into some records.

511
00:36:45,403 --> 00:36:48,873
And I found out that Officer Oda
had questioned Mengqi

512
00:36:49,373 --> 00:36:51,175
for violation of Amusement Business
Control Act.

513
00:36:53,644 --> 00:36:55,246
That was probably

514
00:36:56,247 --> 00:36:59,317
when she thought she could trust him.

515
00:37:01,219 --> 00:37:02,553
Hang on a minute.

516
00:37:03,688 --> 00:37:07,090
Do you think the murder of Lin Mengqi
is connected to Oda?

517
00:37:07,091 --> 00:37:10,928
To figure that out,
I need to clarify a few things.

518
00:37:12,897 --> 00:37:13,998
About four years ago.

519
00:37:15,600 --> 00:37:17,468
I need to know what happened

520
00:37:18,869 --> 00:37:20,004
when Officer Oda died.

521
00:37:23,040 --> 00:37:24,108
I also want to know

522
00:37:25,509 --> 00:37:29,146
what kind of person
Lieutenant Agawa really is.

523
00:37:32,583 --> 00:37:34,252
About the misinterpretation incident

524
00:37:35,586 --> 00:37:37,321
Lieutenant Agawa was involved in.

525
00:37:42,927 --> 00:37:45,329
And the truth about the information leak.

526
00:37:52,003 --> 00:37:53,804
The truth?

527
00:37:55,106 --> 00:37:56,473
Four years have passed already.

528
00:37:56,474 --> 00:37:58,409
Arikeeno, there's something

529
00:38:01,345 --> 00:38:03,547
I want to know more than anything.

530
00:38:06,217 --> 00:38:07,918
I want to know why you're pretending

531
00:38:08,953 --> 00:38:11,555
that you're the one
who leaked the information.

532
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:17,528
Let me be honest with you.

533
00:38:18,596 --> 00:38:20,498
I don't really care

534
00:38:20,998 --> 00:38:23,401
about the police's internal information
being leaked to the press.

535
00:38:25,236 --> 00:38:26,070
But something bothers me.

536
00:38:27,271 --> 00:38:29,840
It bothers me that people hate you,

537
00:38:31,575 --> 00:38:34,245
thinking you're the one
who leaked the information.

538
00:38:37,381 --> 00:38:38,416
Because I know

539
00:38:41,686 --> 00:38:44,088
that you'd never do anything like that.

540
00:38:51,796 --> 00:38:53,564
I knew that this would happen.

541
00:38:55,900 --> 00:38:56,734
Huh?

542
00:38:59,904 --> 00:39:01,505
I knew that some day

543
00:39:03,274 --> 00:39:06,777
you would grill me
about what happened in the past.

544
00:39:13,017 --> 00:39:14,919
I knew that you would start saying

545
00:39:15,653 --> 00:39:17,455
that I'm not that kind of person.

546
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:27,798
When Oda died, I swore to him

547
00:39:29,667 --> 00:39:31,669
that I would bury this case forever.

548
00:39:32,803 --> 00:39:34,070
But still...

549
00:39:34,071 --> 00:39:36,707
Please stop digging into my past.

550
00:39:38,642 --> 00:39:39,910
I beg you.

551
00:39:53,357 --> 00:39:55,126
I'm sorry, but we're closing.

552
00:40:13,077 --> 00:40:14,979
Whoa, taking a trip down memory lane!

553
00:40:16,547 --> 00:40:19,083
It's been five years already, I guess.

554
00:40:20,317 --> 00:40:22,353
They came here together on opening day.

555
00:40:24,088 --> 00:40:25,221
Baijie!

556
00:40:25,222 --> 00:40:26,456
Hey, Satoru!

557
00:40:26,457 --> 00:40:28,459
- Congratulations on your grand opening.
- Thanks!

558
00:40:35,566 --> 00:40:39,136
You can drink from this bottle
even when you come here alone.

559
00:40:40,237 --> 00:40:41,739
I'll never come here alone.

560
00:40:47,778 --> 00:40:48,879
Satoru?

561
00:40:49,580 --> 00:40:51,347
It's you, isn't it?

562
00:40:51,348 --> 00:40:54,050
- It's been ages!
- Hey, you guys.

563
00:40:54,051 --> 00:40:55,318
How have you been?

564
00:40:55,319 --> 00:40:56,719
I've been great.

565
00:40:56,720 --> 00:40:58,656
Long time no see.

566
00:41:00,057 --> 00:41:01,524
Yeah.

567
00:41:01,525 --> 00:41:03,059
You haven't changed at all.

568
00:41:03,060 --> 00:41:05,896
Really? You two haven't changed either.

569
00:41:10,901 --> 00:41:12,136
Mr. Arikino.

570
00:41:14,438 --> 00:41:19,310
You might find it surprising,
but he's very delicate on the inside.

571
00:41:21,512 --> 00:41:23,547
So, take good care of him.

572
00:41:25,716 --> 00:41:26,550
Huh?

573
00:41:30,354 --> 00:41:32,690
<i>I've been so focused on Arikeeno's past</i>

574
00:41:33,824 --> 00:41:36,627
<i>that I'm losing sight of who he really is.</i>

575
00:41:43,300 --> 00:41:45,569
I understand that he's been affected

576
00:41:47,104 --> 00:41:48,973
by losing someone precious to him.

577
00:41:52,643 --> 00:41:54,078
But why on earth

578
00:41:54,945 --> 00:41:56,714
did he have to leave the force?

579
00:41:59,083 --> 00:42:02,753
And why would he shut his heart
so tightly?

580
00:42:07,191 --> 00:42:10,895
What happened between him and Officer Oda?

581
00:42:17,601 --> 00:42:19,503
They may have looked happy,

582
00:42:20,905 --> 00:42:23,674
but whatever happened between them
stays between them.

583
00:42:32,783 --> 00:42:34,318
Maybe you're right.

584
00:42:38,722 --> 00:42:39,657
But...

585
00:42:42,660 --> 00:42:45,429
But I want to know more about Arikeeno.

586
00:42:55,573 --> 00:42:58,508
The series of misinterpretations
appeared to be intentional.

587
00:42:58,509 --> 00:42:59,242
‎NEXT STORY

588
00:42:59,243 --> 00:43:00,711
Will you let me know?

589
00:43:01,278 --> 00:43:04,280
It was Satoru Oda, wasn't it?

590
00:43:04,281 --> 00:43:08,485
<i>Satoru probably couldn't tell him
because he cared about him too much.</i>

591
00:43:09,253 --> 00:43:13,524
Are you planning to do
something by any chance?

592
00:43:31,508 --> 00:43:33,109
FOUR YEARS AGO

593
00:43:33,110 --> 00:43:34,511
‎Don't push me!

594
00:43:35,746 --> 00:43:37,014
Hey, Oda!

595
00:43:37,581 --> 00:43:38,414
Yes, sir.

596
00:43:38,415 --> 00:43:39,549
We have a session.

597
00:43:39,550 --> 00:43:40,650
Yes.

598
00:43:40,651 --> 00:43:42,852
Many women have been brought in

599
00:43:42,853 --> 00:43:45,321
from the raid to an illegal
adult entertainment establishment.

600
00:43:45,322 --> 00:43:48,358
We're expected to verify
their identities one by one

601
00:43:48,359 --> 00:43:51,128
and check with immigration
for their eligibility.

602
00:43:55,165 --> 00:43:56,066
What's wrong?

603
00:43:57,134 --> 00:43:58,335
Got something on my face?

604
00:44:00,404 --> 00:44:01,238
No, sir.

605
00:44:02,006 --> 00:44:03,974
What's going on? You look pale.

606
00:44:05,376 --> 00:44:06,977
Come on, let's get it done.

607
00:44:08,045 --> 00:44:08,979
Yes, sir.
